# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Capacity config for an always-on run — the ToS-clean lane.
#
# Copy this to a file named `.env` (or wherever your runner reads credentials),
# fill in YOUR values, and keep it OUT of git. Lock it down:
#     cp gateway.env.example .env
#     chmod 600 .env
#
# This file describes the RECOMMENDED capacity setup: one budgeted API key with
# a spending cap, plus a fallback route. That's it. There is deliberately no
# option here for pooling subscription logins behind a proxy — see the red line
# at the bottom for why.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

# --- Primary: your budgeted, metered API key (the recommended lane) ----------
# This is a developer/API key from your provider's console, NOT your chat
# subscription login. It's meant to be used by tools, and you can put a hard
# spending cap on it. Keep this secret; never commit it, never share it.
PRIMARY_API_KEY=your-metered-api-key-goes-here

# A label for your primary provider (used only for readable preflight output).
PRIMARY_PROVIDER=anthropic

# Set this to "yes" ONLY after you have set a monthly spending cap in your
# provider's billing console. The cap is what makes walking away safe: a runaway
# overnight job hits the cap and STOPS instead of running up a surprise bill.
PRIMARY_SPEND_CAP_SET=no

# --- Fallback: keep working when the primary is busy or down -----------------
# Provide EITHER a second provider's API key OR a local model CLI command name.
# Either one gives the runner somewhere to go if the primary returns a "slow
# down" (429) or is temporarily unavailable. Fill in ONE of the two.

# Option A — a second provider's budgeted API key:
FALLBACK_API_KEY=

# Option B — a local model CLI already installed on your PATH (leave A blank):
# FALLBACK_CLI=your-local-model-cli

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# RED LINE — read this before you get "creative" about capacity.
#
# When you need MORE capacity, do exactly one of these:
#   1. Raise the spending cap on your budgeted API key (more headroom, still yours).
#   2. Stagger your jobs so they don't all pile onto the same window.
#   3. Add a genuine second provider on the fallback route above.
#
# Do NOT pool multiple personal SUBSCRIPTION logins behind a shared proxy/relay
# to fake more throughput. That is a named, enforced Anthropic ToS violation
# (in effect since Feb 2026) and it gets EVERY account in the pool banned — not
# one, all of them. Owning multiple accounts is fine; POOLING their logins
# through a proxy is the violation. There is no config line for it here on
# purpose.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
